BBEX3.D.ATS.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: From 26 May 1954 to 31 December 1956, foreign-exchange conversion rates of the Bank deutscher Länder (the predecessor of the Deutsche Bundesbank). From 2 January 1957 to 30 December 1998, official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange (difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate DEM 0.020). From 1 January 1999, irrevocable euro conversion rate: EUR 1 = ATS 13.7603.
BBEX3.D.BEF.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: From 21 December 1949 to 3 May 1953, foreign-exchange conversion rates of the Bank deutscher Länder (the predecessor of the Deutsche Bundesbank). From 4 May 1953 to 30 December 1998, official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange (difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate DEM 0.0100). In accordance with a resolution by the management board of the Frankfurt exchange, with effect from January 1994 the exchange rate of the Belgian franc was set at four decimal places. For technical reasons, the exchange rates up to December 1993 were extended from three to four decimal places. Please notice: from June 1954 to January 1955 some of the exchange rates for the Belgian franc were quoted with four decimal places. From 1 January 1999, irrevocable euro conversion rate: EUR 1 = BEF 40.3399.
BBEX3.D.CAD.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: Difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate in DEM: 0.0050 up to the end of August 1978, 0.0040 since September 1978. From 11 May 1953 to 30 December 1998 official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange. From January 1999, euro foreign exchange reference rates published by the European Central Bank.
BBEX3.D.CHF.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: From 21 December 1949 to 3 May 1953, foreign-exchange conversion rates of the Bank deutscher Länder (the predecessor of the Deutsche Bundesbank).   From 4 May to 25 July 1953, exchange rates for the Swiss franc under exchange rate agreements. These were set alongside the official quotation until 24 December 1958. From 27 July 1953 to 30 December 1998, official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange (difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate DEM 0.100). From January 1999, euro foreign exchange reference rates published by the European Central Bank, see BBEX3:D:CHF:EUR:BB:AC:000.
BBEX3.D.DKK.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: From 21 December 1949 to 17 May 1953, foreign-exchange conversion rates of the Bank deutscher Länder (the predecessor of the Deutsche Bundesbank). From 18 May 1953 to 30 December 1998, official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange (difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate DEM 0.060). From January 1999, euro foreign exchange reference rates published by the European Central Bank, see BBEX3:D:DKK:EUR:BB:AC:000.
BBEX3.D.ESP.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: Difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate in DEM: 0.010 up to the end of August 1978, 0.005 up to the end of 1993, 0.0040 since 1994. From 18 February 1963 to 30 December 1998 official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange. In accordance with a resolution by the management board of the Frankfurt exchange, with effect from January 1994 the exchange rate of the peseta was set at four decimal places. For technical reasons, the exchange rates up to December 1993 were extended from three to four decimal places. From 1 January 1999, irrevocable euro conversion rate: EUR 1 = ESP 166.386.
BBEX3.D.FIM.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: Difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate in DEM: 0.100 up to the end of 1993, 0.080 since 1994. From 17 July 1972 to 30 December 1998 official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange. From 1 January 1999, irrevocable euro conversion rate: EUR 1 = FIM 5.94573.
BBEX3.D.FRF.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: From 13 February 1950 to 3 May 1953, foreign-exchange conversion rates of the Bank deutscher Länder (the predecessor of the Deutsche Bundesbank). From 4 May 1953 to 30 December 1998, official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange (difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate in DEM: 0.0010 up to the end of December 1959, 0.100 up to the end of August 1978, 0.080 up to the end of 1993, 0.060 since 1994). Currency conversion with effect from 1 January 1960: 100 French francs = 1 French new franc, designated as French franc since 1 January 1963. For technical reasons, the exchange rates from 1 January 1960 were extended from three to four decimal places. From 1 January 1999, irrevocable euro conversion rate: EUR 1 = FRF 6.55957.
BBEX3.D.GBP.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: From 21 December 1949 to 17 May 1953, foreign-exchange conversion rates of the Bank deutscher Länder (the predecessor of the Deutsche Bundesbank). From 18 May 1953 to 30 December 1998, official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange (difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate in DEM: 0.010 up to the end of August 1978, 0.0070 since September 1978). In accordance with a resolution by the management board of the Frankfurt exchange, with effect from January 1994 the exchange rate of the pound sterling was set at four decimal places. For technical reasons, the exchange rates up to December 1993 were extended from three to four decimal places. Please notice: from June 1954 to January 1955 some of the exchange rates for the pound sterling were quoted with four decimal places. From January 1999, euro foreign exchange reference rates published by the European Central Bank, see BBEX3:D:GBP:EUR:BB:AC:000.
BBEX3.D.IEP.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: From 21 December 1951 to 17 May 1953, foreign-exchange conversion rates of the Bank deutscher Länder (the predecessor of the Deutsche Bundesbank).   From 18 May 1953 to 12 March 1979, exchange rates for the pound sterling (parity with the pound sterling).  From 13 March 1979 to 30 December 1998, official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange (difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate DEM 0.0070). In accordance with a resolution by the management board of the Frankfurt exchange, with effect from January 1994 the exchange rate of the Irish pound was set at four decimal places. For technical reasons, the exchange rates up to December 1993 were extended from three to four decimal places. From 1 January 1999, irrevocable euro conversion rate: EUR 1 = IEP 0.787564.
BBEX3.D.ITL.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: From 31 October 1950 to 21 August 1955, foreign-exchange conversion rates of the Bank deutscher Länder (the predecessor of the Deutsche Bundesbank). From 22 August 1955 to 30 December 1998, official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange (difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate in DEM: 0.010 up to the end of August 1978, 0.0050 up to the end of 1993, 0.0040 since 1994). In accordance with a resolution by the management board of the Frankfurt exchange, with effect from May 1985 the exchange rate of the Italian lira was set at four decimal places. For technical reasons, the exchange rates up to April 1985 were extended from three to four decimal places. From 1 January 1999, irrevocable euro conversion rate: EUR 1 = ITL 1,936.27.
BBEX3.D.JPY.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: Difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate DEM 0.0015. From 1 December 1969 to 30 December 1998 official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange. From January 1999, euro foreign exchange reference rates published by the European Central Bank.
BBEX3.D.NLG.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: From 21 December 1949 to 3 May 1953, foreign-exchange conversion rates of the Bank deutscher Länder (the predecessor of the Deutsche Bundesbank). From 4 May 1953 to 30 December 1998, official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange (difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate DEM 0.110). From 1 January 1999, irrevocable euro conversion rate: EUR 1 = NLG 2.20371.
BBEX3.D.NOK.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: From 21 December 1949 to 13 December 1953, foreign-exchange conversion rates of the Bank deutscher Länder (the predecessor of the Deutsche Bundesbank). From 14 December 1953 to 30 December 1998, official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange (difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate DEM 0.060). From January 1999, euro foreign exchange reference rates published by the European Central Bank, see BBEX3:D:NOK:EUR:BB:AC:000.
BBEX3.D.PTE.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: From 14 May 1952 to 28 December 1958, foreign-exchange conversion rates of the Bank deutscher Länder (the predecessor of the Deutsche Bundesbank).  From 29 December 1958 to 30 December 1998, official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange (difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate in DEM: 0.020 up to the end of August 1978, 0.010 up to the end of 1993, 0.0030 since 1994).  In accordance with a resolution by the management board of the Frankfurt exchange, with effect from January 1994 the exchange rate of the escudo was set at four decimal places. For technical reasons, the exchange rates up to December 1993 were extended from three to four decimal places. From 1 January 1999, irrevocable euro conversion rate: EUR 1 = PTE 200.482.
BBEX3.D.SEK.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: From 21 December 1949 to 17 May 1953, foreign-exchange conversion rates of the Bank deutscher Länder (the predecessor of the Deutsche Bundesbank). From 18 May 1953 to 30 December 1998, official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange (difference between buying or selling rate in DEM: 0.080 up to the end of 1993, 0.060 since 1994). From January 1999, euro foreign exchange reference rates published by the European Central Bank, see BBEX3:D:SEK:EUR:BB:AC:000.
BBEX3.D.USD.DEM.AA.AC.000: General: Until 16 September 1949, reciprocal value of the conversion rate of DEM 1 = USD 0.30 fixed by the Joint Export Import Agency (JEIA) in accordance with Operational Memorandum No. 25, Amendment No. 1.  From 19 September 1949 to 9 August 1953, foreign-exchange conversion rates of the Bank deutscher Länder (the predecessor of the Deutsche Bundesbank).   From 10 August 1953 to 30 December 1998, official quotation on the Frankfurt exchange (difference between buying or selling rate and middle rate in DEM: 0.0050 up to the end of August 1978, 0.0040 since September 1978). From January 1999, euro foreign exchange reference rates published by the European Central Bank, see BBEX3:D:USD:EUR:BB:AC:000.
